/* CRISC :: content/quiz2.js — CRISC Domain 2 question bank (100 items). */
window.CRISC = window.CRISC || {}; CRISC.questions = CRISC.questions || [];
CRISC.questions.push.apply(CRISC.questions, [
{"id":"D2-001","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"easy","q":"A risk practitioner is documenting a new entry in the risk register after a payment-processing outage. Which of the following BEST completes a well-formed risk statement?","options":["The event, the affected asset, and the potential business impact","The name of the employee who reported the outage","The brand of server hardware involved","The date the incident ticket was closed"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The event, the affected asset, and the potential business impact</strong> — a usable risk statement links a specific loss-event type to the asset at risk and expresses the consequence in business terms so it can be assessed and prioritized.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The name of the employee who reported the outage</b>: reporter identity has no bearing on the substance of the risk itself.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The brand of server hardware involved</b>: vendor/hardware detail may support root-cause analysis but is not what makes a risk statement usable for prioritization.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The date the incident ticket was closed</b>: ticket closure is an operational tracking detail, not part of the risk statement.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-002","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of an integrity loss-event type, as opposed to availability or confidentiality?","options":["A ransomware attack encrypts the file server, taking it offline","An unauthorized party modifies financial transaction records without detection","A laptop containing unencrypted customer records is stolen","A denial-of-service attack floods a public web application"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>An unauthorized party modifies financial transaction records without detection</strong> — integrity loss events involve unauthorized alteration of data or systems, which is exactly what unauthorized modification of transaction records represents.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A ransomware attack encrypts the file server, taking it offline</b>: this primarily represents an availability loss, since the data is not altered but access to it is denied.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A laptop containing unencrypted customer records is stolen</b>: this is a confidentiality loss event, since sensitive data may be disclosed to an unauthorized party.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A denial-of-service attack floods a public web application</b>: this is a classic availability loss event, not an integrity concern.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-003","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is categorizing recent loss events for trend analysis. An employee accidentally emails a spreadsheet containing customer PII to the wrong external recipient. This is BEST classified as which loss-event type?","options":["Availability loss due to a technical failure","Integrity loss due to malicious tampering","Confidentiality loss due to human error","Compliance loss due to a missed regulatory filing"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Confidentiality loss due to human error</strong> — sensitive data was disclosed to an unintended party through a mistake, which is the defining characteristic of a confidentiality-related loss event driven by human error rather than malice or a technical fault.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Availability loss due to a technical failure</b>: no system or data access was disrupted; the data remained accessible, just wrongly disclosed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Integrity loss due to malicious tampering</b>: the data itself was not altered, and the disclosure was accidental rather than malicious tampering.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Compliance loss due to a missed regulatory filing</b>: no filing deadline is described; the event is a data-handling mistake, not a missed filing.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-004","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"hard","q":"Over the past year, a risk practitioner notices that a disproportionate share of logged loss events fall under \"process failure\" rather than \"malicious attack\" or \"natural disaster.\" What is the MOST appropriate next step?","options":["Reclassify all process-failure events as malicious attacks to simplify reporting","Discontinue tracking loss-event types since the categories overlap","Report only the malicious-attack category to senior management going forward","Investigate whether specific process weaknesses are recurring across business units and drive a targeted root-cause review"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Investigate whether specific process weaknesses are recurring across business units and drive a targeted root-cause review</strong> — a skewed distribution toward process failure is a signal that systemic process gaps may exist, and the practitioner's role is to translate that pattern into a targeted investigation rather than ignore or obscure it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reclassify all process-failure events as malicious attacks to simplify reporting</b>: this misrepresents the actual cause of events and would corrupt trend analysis.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Discontinue tracking loss-event types since the categories overlap</b>: abandoning categorization removes a valuable analytical tool rather than resolving the overlap.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Report only the malicious-attack category to senior management going forward</b>: suppressing the dominant category would hide the most relevant risk signal from decision-makers.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-005","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following loss-event types is MOST directly associated with a third-party cloud provider suffering a multi-region service disruption?","options":["Availability","Confidentiality","Integrity","Compliance"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Availability</strong> — a service disruption that prevents access to systems or data for legitimate users is the defining characteristic of an availability loss event.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality</b>: a disruption in service does not by itself imply that data was disclosed to unauthorized parties.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Integrity</b>: nothing in the scenario indicates data was altered or corrupted.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Compliance</b>: while a lengthy outage might eventually trigger compliance concerns, the primary and direct loss-event type is availability.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-006","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of threat modeling during risk identification?","options":["To calculate the exact dollar value of a potential loss","To systematically identify how specific threat actors could exploit a system's design to cause harm","To assign a risk owner to each identified vulnerability","To determine the organization's overall risk appetite"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To systematically identify how specific threat actors could exploit a system's design to cause harm</strong> — threat modeling is a structured technique for examining an asset or system's architecture to anticipate realistic attack paths before they are exploited.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To calculate the exact dollar value of a potential loss</b>: monetary loss calculation is a quantitative risk analysis activity, not the purpose of threat modeling.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To assign a risk owner to each identified vulnerability</b>: ownership assignment is a governance activity separate from the technical exercise of threat modeling.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To determine the organization's overall risk appetite</b>: risk appetite is a strategic decision made by senior management, unrelated to threat modeling technique.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-007","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is assessing which threat actors are most relevant to a mid-sized healthcare provider. Which factor should MOST influence this determination?","options":["The number of firewalls the organization currently has deployed","The personal preferences of the risk practitioner","The motive and capability of each actor type relative to the organization's specific assets and industry","The most frequently discussed threat actor in general media coverage"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The motive and capability of each actor type relative to the organization's specific assets and industry</strong> — relevance is determined by whether a given actor has both the motive (e.g., financial gain from patient data) and the capability to target the organization's actual assets, not by generic popularity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The number of firewalls the organization currently has deployed</b>: control counts do not determine which threat actors are relevant to the organization.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The personal preferences of the risk practitioner</b>: threat relevance must be evidence-based, not a matter of individual preference.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The most frequently discussed threat actor in general media coverage</b>: media attention does not equate to actual relevance to a specific organization's risk profile.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-008","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner reviews a threat intelligence report describing a new attack technique already used against three competitors. What is the MOST appropriate FIRST step?","options":["Immediately deploy a new control regardless of applicability","Forward the report to the board without further analysis","Dismiss the report because it targets competitors, not the organization directly","Determine whether the organization has the vulnerable technology or process the technique exploits"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Determine whether the organization has the vulnerable technology or process the technique exploits</strong> — before deciding on any action, the practitioner must assess relevance by checking whether the organization's own environment contains the exploitable condition described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately deploy a new control regardless of applicability</b>: reacting before establishing relevance risks wasted effort and misallocated resources.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Forward the report to the board without further analysis</b>: sending unanalyzed threat data to the board provides no actionable business context.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Dismiss the report because it targets competitors, not the organization directly</b>: shared industry exposure means the technique could plausibly apply to the organization as well, so dismissal without analysis is premature.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-009","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"med","q":"Which threat actor category is generally characterized by ideological or political motivation rather than financial gain?","options":["Hacktivists","Organized cybercriminal groups","Nation-state actors seeking espionage","Insiders motivated by financial hardship"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Hacktivists</strong> — this actor category is driven by ideological or political grievances, typically using denial-of-service or defacement to generate visibility for a cause rather than pursue profit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Organized cybercriminal groups</b>: these actors are financially motivated, operating extortion and fraud schemes for profit.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Nation-state actors seeking espionage</b>: this category is driven by strategic or geopolitical objectives, not ideology in the activist sense.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Insiders motivated by financial hardship</b>: this describes a financially motivated insider threat, not an ideologically driven external actor.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-010","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST defines a vulnerability in the context of risk assessment?","options":["A potential source of harm to the organization","A weakness in an asset or control that could be exploited by a threat","The monetary value assigned to an asset","The likelihood that a risk event will occur"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A weakness in an asset or control that could be exploited by a threat</strong> — a vulnerability is the exploitable gap in a system, process, or control, distinct from the threat that might exploit it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A potential source of harm to the organization</b>: this describes a threat, not a vulnerability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The monetary value assigned to an asset</b>: this describes asset value, a separate input to quantitative risk analysis.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The likelihood that a risk event will occur</b>: likelihood is a probability estimate used in risk analysis, not the definition of a vulnerability itself.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-011","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"med","q":"A vulnerability scan identifies a critical flaw on an internal, fully isolated test system with no path to sensitive data, while the same technical severity flaw exists on an internet-facing production system. Which system should the risk practitioner prioritize for remediation?","options":["The isolated test system, because it was discovered first","Both systems equally, since the technical severity score is identical","The internet-facing production system, because exposure and asset value increase the actual risk","Neither system, since both scored as critical and require executive escalation only"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The internet-facing production system, because exposure and asset value increase the actual risk</strong> — risk-based prioritization considers exploitability and exposure alongside asset value, not just the raw technical severity score, so the exposed production system represents materially higher actual risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The isolated test system, because it was discovered first</b>: discovery order is irrelevant to risk-based prioritization.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Both systems equally, since the technical severity score is identical</b>: treating them equally ignores the very different exposure and business context of each system.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Neither system, since both scored as critical and require executive escalation only</b>: escalation does not replace the need to prioritize and remediate based on actual risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-012","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"hard","q":"An internal audit reports the same access-review control deficiency for the third consecutive quarter, each time with a new remediation target date. What is the MOST appropriate action for the risk practitioner?","options":["Accept a fourth extension since the process owner is clearly working on it","Remove the finding from tracking since it has been reported multiple times already","Personally perform the access reviews to close the finding","Escalate the recurring pattern to senior management as a systemic accountability issue"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Escalate the recurring pattern to senior management as a systemic accountability issue</strong> — a repeatedly missed remediation date signals a deeper ownership or resourcing problem that requires management attention beyond another routine extension.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Accept a fourth extension since the process owner is clearly working on it</b>: repeated extensions without escalation allow the underlying risk to persist unmanaged.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Remove the finding from tracking since it has been reported multiple times already</b>: removing visibility hides an unresolved risk rather than addressing it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Personally perform the access reviews to close the finding</b>: the practitioner taking over the control undermines accountability and does not fix the systemic issue.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-013","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"med","q":"Which vulnerability identification method is BEST suited to demonstrate real-world exploitability by chaining multiple weaknesses together?","options":["Penetration testing","Automated vulnerability scanning only","A control self-assessment questionnaire","A review of the organization's asset inventory"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Penetration testing</strong> — skilled testers actively chain vulnerabilities together to demonstrate real exploitability and business impact, going beyond what automated scanning alone can show.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Automated vulnerability scanning only</b>: scanning provides broad, frequent coverage of known weaknesses but does not demonstrate chained exploitability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A control self-assessment questionnaire</b>: self-assessments surface process and people gaps through owner input, not technical exploit chains.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A review of the organization's asset inventory</b>: an inventory review identifies what exists, not how weaknesses could be exploited together.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-014","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of developing risk scenarios during risk assessment?","options":["To replace the need for a risk register","To translate abstract threats and vulnerabilities into plausible, specific situations that can be analyzed for likelihood and impact","To satisfy a one-time annual compliance requirement","To eliminate the need for a business impact analysis"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To translate abstract threats and vulnerabilities into plausible, specific situations that can be analyzed for likelihood and impact</strong> — risk scenarios make risk tangible and assessable by describing a concrete sequence of events involving a specific asset, threat, and vulnerability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To replace the need for a risk register</b>: scenarios feed into the risk register; they do not replace it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To satisfy a one-time annual compliance requirement</b>: scenario development is an ongoing analytical practice, not a one-time compliance box to check.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To eliminate the need for a business impact analysis</b>: scenarios and BIA are complementary, distinct activities that both inform risk analysis.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-015","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is developing a risk scenario for a new cloud-based HR system. Which approach is MOST likely to produce a scenario that is both specific and analyzable?","options":["Write a general statement such as \"the system might be hacked\"","List every possible threat actor in the industry without linking them to the system","Combine a defined threat source, an exploitable condition, the affected asset, and the resulting business impact into one coherent narrative","Copy a generic scenario template from an unrelated organization without modification"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Combine a defined threat source, an exploitable condition, the affected asset, and the resulting business impact into one coherent narrative</strong> — a well-formed scenario names all the risk components together so likelihood and impact can be meaningfully estimated and tracked.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Write a general statement such as \"the system might be hacked\"</b>: this vague statement lacks the specificity needed to assess likelihood or impact.</span> <span class='qd'><b>List every possible threat actor in the industry without linking them to the system</b>: an unlinked list does not constitute an analyzable scenario tied to the actual asset.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Copy a generic scenario template from an unrelated organization without modification</b>: an unmodified generic template will not reflect the organization's actual context and exposure.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-016","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner facilitates a scenario workshop and produces two candidate scenarios: one broad (\"a cyberattack disrupts operations\") and one specific (\"a ransomware variant encrypts the order-management database during peak season, halting order processing for 3-5 days\"). Which scenario BEST supports risk evaluation, and why?","options":["The broad scenario, because it covers more possible outcomes at once","Both are equally useful since they describe the same underlying risk","Neither scenario is useful without a completed penetration test first","The specific scenario, because it enables meaningful likelihood and impact estimation tied to a defined asset and timeframe"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The specific scenario, because it enables meaningful likelihood and impact estimation tied to a defined asset and timeframe</strong> — specificity about the asset, threat, timing, and consequence is what allows the practitioner to actually estimate likelihood and impact and assign ownership and treatment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The broad scenario, because it covers more possible outcomes at once</b>: breadth without specificity makes the scenario impossible to analyze or act on.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Both are equally useful since they describe the same underlying risk</b>: the two scenarios differ significantly in analyzability, so they are not equally useful.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Neither scenario is useful without a completed penetration test first</b>: scenario development does not require a penetration test as a prerequisite.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-017","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"easy","q":"Which risk identification technique brings cross-functional stakeholders together to walk through plausible sequences of events that could affect the organization?","options":["Scenario analysis and workshops","Automated vulnerability scanning","Financial statement audit","Firewall log review"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Scenario analysis and workshops</strong> — this technique convenes stakeholders from across the business to collaboratively surface risks that a purely technical or asset-based approach might miss.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Automated vulnerability scanning</b>: this is a technical identification method, not a cross-functional collaborative technique.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Financial statement audit</b>: this is a finance-specific assurance activity, not a general risk identification workshop technique.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Firewall log review</b>: this is a technical monitoring activity focused on network traffic, not scenario-based identification.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-018","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"med","q":"Why should risk identification rely on multiple techniques (asset-based, threat-based, scenario workshops, process walkthroughs) rather than a single method?","options":["Because regulators mandate the use of exactly four techniques","Because each technique surfaces different types of risk, and relying on only one leaves significant blind spots","Because using multiple techniques eliminates the need for a risk register","Because a single technique always takes longer than several combined"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Because each technique surfaces different types of risk, and relying on only one leaves significant blind spots</strong> — asset-based, threat-based, and workshop-driven approaches each reveal risks the others might miss, so a comprehensive program combines them.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Because regulators mandate the use of exactly four techniques</b>: there is no universal regulatory mandate specifying an exact number of techniques.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Because using multiple techniques eliminates the need for a risk register</b>: the register is still required regardless of how many identification techniques are used.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Because a single technique always takes longer than several combined</b>: this is not generally true and is not the reason multiple techniques are recommended.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-019","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner relies exclusively on an asset inventory to drive risk identification for a new product line. What is the MOST significant limitation of this approach?","options":["It produces results too quickly for management to review","It requires no input from business unit stakeholders at all, which is inherently a flaw","It may miss risks arising from threats and process weaknesses that are not tied to a specific listed asset","It automatically overstates every risk's likelihood"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>It may miss risks arising from threats and process weaknesses that are not tied to a specific listed asset</strong> — an asset-only approach can overlook process, people, or emerging threat-driven risks that do not map cleanly to an inventoried asset, which is why complementary techniques are needed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It produces results too quickly for management to review</b>: speed of output is not a meaningful limitation of the technique.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It requires no input from business unit stakeholders at all, which is inherently a flaw</b>: this describes a possible symptom of poor execution, not the core structural limitation of asset-based identification.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It automatically overstates every risk's likelihood</b>: asset-based identification does not inherently bias likelihood estimates in one direction.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-020","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of a documented risk assessment methodology?","options":["To guarantee that no risk will ever materialize","To replace the need for a risk register","To satisfy only external audit requirements once per year","To ensure risk is analyzed consistently across the organization using defined criteria for likelihood and impact"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>To ensure risk is analyzed consistently across the organization using defined criteria for likelihood and impact</strong> — a documented methodology provides repeatable, comparable criteria so that risk ratings from different assessors and business units mean the same thing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To guarantee that no risk will ever materialize</b>: no methodology can guarantee the absence of future risk events.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To replace the need for a risk register</b>: the methodology governs how risks are analyzed; the register is where results are recorded, and one does not replace the other.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To satisfy only external audit requirements once per year</b>: a methodology supports ongoing, continuous risk management, not merely an annual audit exercise.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-021","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"med","q":"An organization wants risk ratings from IT, finance, and operations to be directly comparable for enterprise prioritization. Which action BEST supports this goal?","options":["Adopt a common risk assessment standard and rating scale used consistently across all business units","Allow each business unit to define its own independent rating scale","Limit risk assessment activity to the IT department only","Use quantitative analysis in IT and purely subjective judgment everywhere else"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Adopt a common risk assessment standard and rating scale used consistently across all business units</strong> — a shared standard and scale is what makes risk ratings from different functions genuinely comparable for enterprise-wide prioritization.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allow each business unit to define its own independent rating scale</b>: independent scales make cross-functional comparison unreliable or impossible.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Limit risk assessment activity to the IT department only</b>: excluding other functions ignores risks originating outside IT.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Use quantitative analysis in IT and purely subjective judgment everywhere else</b>: inconsistent analytical approaches across functions undermines comparability.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-022","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"hard","q":"An organization has adopted a recognized risk assessment standard (e.g., ISO/IEC 27005 or NIST SP 800-30) but individual assessors still apply differing informal criteria for rating impact. What is the MOST likely underlying cause?","options":["The chosen standard is legally invalid in most jurisdictions","The standard has not been operationalized into a specific, organization-tailored methodology with defined rating criteria","Standards adoption automatically guarantees rating consistency without further action","The organization should abandon the standard and use no methodology at all"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The standard has not been operationalized into a specific, organization-tailored methodology with defined rating criteria</strong> — a high-level standard provides a framework, but it must be translated into concrete, organization-specific rating definitions and criteria before assessors can apply it consistently.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The chosen standard is legally invalid in most jurisdictions</b>: recognized risk standards are voluntary frameworks, not something invalidated by jurisdiction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Standards adoption automatically guarantees rating consistency without further action</b>: simply adopting a standard's name does not by itself produce consistent practice.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization should abandon the standard and use no methodology at all</b>: removing methodology entirely would worsen, not fix, the inconsistency problem.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-023","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the BEST definition of a key risk indicator (KRI)?","options":["A list of all controls currently implemented across the enterprise","A summary of the prior year's audit findings","A metric that provides early warning of increasing risk exposure in a specific area","A count of completed security awareness training sessions"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A metric that provides early warning of increasing risk exposure in a specific area</strong> — KRIs are forward-looking, leading metrics designed to signal rising risk before a loss event actually occurs, enabling proactive response.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A list of all controls currently implemented across the enterprise</b>: this describes a control inventory, not a risk indicator.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A summary of the prior year's audit findings</b>: audit findings are a point-in-time assurance output, not an ongoing leading indicator.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A count of completed security awareness training sessions</b>: a training completion count is a performance/output metric, not a leading risk signal.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-024","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a business impact analysis (BIA)?","options":["To calculate the exact monetary loss expectancy for every asset in the organization","To assign risk owners to each entry in the risk register","To determine the organization's overall risk appetite statement","To identify critical business processes and quantify the impact of their disruption over time"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>To identify critical business processes and quantify the impact of their disruption over time</strong> — a BIA determines which processes are critical, how quickly their loss becomes damaging, and what resources are needed to recover them within tolerable timeframes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To calculate the exact monetary loss expectancy for every asset in the organization</b>: SLE/ALE calculations are a quantitative risk analysis activity distinct from a BIA's focus on process criticality and recovery needs.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To assign risk owners to each entry in the risk register</b>: ownership assignment is a governance activity separate from BIA's process-impact focus.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To determine the organization's overall risk appetite statement</b>: risk appetite is set by senior management as a strategic decision, not derived directly from a BIA.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-025","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"med","q":"A BIA determines that the order-management system can be unavailable for a maximum of 8 hours before the organization suffers unacceptable harm. This threshold is BEST described as the:","options":["Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD)","Recovery point objective (RPO)","Single loss expectancy (SLE)","Annualized rate of occurrence (ARO)"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD)</strong> — this is the outer limit of disruption a business function can withstand before unacceptable harm occurs, which is exactly what the 8-hour threshold represents.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Recovery point objective (RPO)</b>: RPO measures the maximum tolerable data loss measured in time, not downtime duration.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Single loss expectancy (SLE)</b>: SLE is a monetary figure representing the expected loss from a single event, unrelated to a downtime threshold.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Annualized rate of occurrence (ARO)</b>: ARO is the expected frequency of an event per year, not a downtime tolerance.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-026","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"hard","q":"A BIA reveals that the payroll process has a recovery point objective (RPO) of 4 hours, but the current backup schedule only runs every 24 hours. What is the MOST significant risk this gap creates?","options":["The organization will automatically fail its next external audit","Up to 24 hours of payroll data could be unrecoverable in a disruption, far exceeding the tolerable data-loss window","The RPO must be increased to match the backup schedule with no further analysis needed","No risk exists as long as the RTO is met"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Up to 24 hours of payroll data could be unrecoverable in a disruption, far exceeding the tolerable data-loss window</strong> — a backup schedule that runs less frequently than the defined RPO means actual potential data loss significantly exceeds what the business has determined it can tolerate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization will automatically fail its next external audit</b>: while this gap could raise audit concerns, that is not the direct, primary risk it creates.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The RPO must be increased to match the backup schedule with no further analysis needed</b>: silently relaxing the RPO to match operational reality bypasses proper risk evaluation and business input.</span> <span class='qd'><b>No risk exists as long as the RTO is met</b>: meeting the recovery time objective does not address the separate, significant data-loss exposure created by the RPO gap.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-027","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"easy","q":"An asset has an asset value (AV) of $400,000 and an exposure factor (EF) of 25% for a specific threat. What is the single loss expectancy (SLE)?","options":["$400,000","$25,000","$100,000","$160,000"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>$100,000</strong> — SLE = AV x EF = $400,000 x 0.25 = $100,000.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>$400,000</b>: this is the full asset value, ignoring the exposure factor entirely.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$25,000</b>: does not correspond to the correct multiplication of the given AV and EF.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$160,000</b>: results from an incorrect exposure factor (40%) rather than the given 25%.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-028","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"med","q":"A risk has an SLE of $60,000 and an annualized rate of occurrence (ARO) of 0.5 (expected once every two years). What is the annualized loss expectancy (ALE)?","options":["$120,000","$60,000","$12,000","$30,000"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>$30,000</strong> — ALE = SLE x ARO = $60,000 x 0.5 = $30,000.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>$120,000</b>: results from dividing rather than multiplying, incorrectly treating ARO as a divisor.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$60,000</b>: this is only the SLE, ignoring the frequency of occurrence.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$12,000</b>: results from using an incorrect ARO of 0.2 instead of the given 0.5.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-029","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"hard","q":"An asset worth $3,000,000 faces a threat with an exposure factor of 20%. The threat is expected to occur three times every 5 years. What is the ALE?","options":["$360,000","$600,000","$150,000","$180,000"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>$360,000</strong> — SLE = AV x EF = $3,000,000 x 0.20 = $600,000. ARO = 3/5 = 0.6. ALE = SLE x ARO = $600,000 x 0.6 = $360,000.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>$600,000</b>: this is the SLE value only, without applying the annualized rate of occurrence.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$150,000</b>: does not correspond to the correct multiplication of SLE and ARO using the given figures.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$180,000</b>: results from an incorrect ARO of 0.3 rather than the correct 0.6.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-030","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"med","q":"A proposed control costs $20,000 annually and is expected to reduce ALE from $90,000 to $50,000. What is the return on security investment (ROSI)?","options":["45%","100%","200%","55%"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>100%</strong> — ROSI = (Risk reduction - Cost of control) / Cost of control = (($90,000 - $50,000) - $20,000) / $20,000 = $20,000 / $20,000 = 100%.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>45%</b>: does not match the risk-reduction-minus-cost-over-cost formula using the figures given.</span> <span class='qd'><b>200%</b>: represents the gross benefit-to-cost ratio ($40,000/$20,000) without properly forming the net ROSI ratio.</span> <span class='qd'><b>55%</b>: does not correspond to a correct calculation using the given figures.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-031","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the primary purpose of a risk register?","options":["To list every technical vulnerability found during a single penetration test","To document the results of the most recent compliance audit only","To provide a centralized, living record of identified risks, their analysis, and treatment status","To track help desk tickets related to security incidents"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To provide a centralized, living record of identified risks, their analysis, and treatment status</strong> — the risk register is the authoritative repository tracking each risk from identification through analysis, treatment decision, ownership, and ongoing status.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To list every technical vulnerability found during a single penetration test</b>: a vulnerability list is only one input feeding the register, not the register itself.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To document the results of the most recent compliance audit only</b>: audit findings are a separate output that may feed the register but do not define its overall purpose.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To track help desk tickets related to security incidents</b>: incident tickets belong to incident management, not enterprise risk tracking.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-032","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"med","q":"A risk register entry has been open for 18 months with no update to its treatment plan or status. What is the MOST appropriate action for the risk practitioner?","options":["Delete the entry since it is clearly no longer relevant","Automatically escalate the risk owner for termination","Leave the entry unchanged since it was already documented once","Follow up with the risk owner to obtain a current status and revalidate whether the risk and treatment plan are still accurate"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Follow up with the risk owner to obtain a current status and revalidate whether the risk and treatment plan are still accurate</strong> — a stale entry must be revisited to confirm whether the risk level, controls, and treatment plan still reflect current reality, since a living register requires ongoing maintenance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delete the entry since it is clearly no longer relevant</b>: deleting without validation could remove a risk that remains very much active.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Automatically escalate the risk owner for termination</b>: this is a disproportionate personnel action not supported by the scenario.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Leave the entry unchanged since it was already documented once</b>: leaving a stale entry unchanged undermines the register's accuracy and value.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-033","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"hard","q":"A risk register contains hundreds of entries, but the risk committee finds it nearly impossible to identify which risks matter most because entries lack consistent categorization. What is the BEST way to address this?","options":["Implement a consistent risk categorization scheme (e.g., cyber, third-party, operational) to enable meaningful aggregation and roll-up reporting","Delete older entries to reduce the total register size","Require the committee to read every individual entry line by line at each meeting","Move the register to a spreadsheet with no defined fields for flexibility"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Implement a consistent risk categorization scheme (e.g., cyber, third-party, operational) to enable meaningful aggregation and roll-up reporting</strong> — consistent categorization allows risks to be grouped and rolled up so that leadership can see aggregate exposure and priorities without manually parsing every line.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delete older entries to reduce the total register size</b>: removing entries without justification hides risk rather than improving usability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Require the committee to read every individual entry line by line at each meeting</b>: this is impractical at scale and does not solve the underlying reporting problem.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Move the register to a spreadsheet with no defined fields for flexibility</b>: removing structure would make aggregation and consistency even harder to achieve.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-034","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following fields in a risk register entry is MOST important for showing how much value the current control environment provides for a specific risk?","options":["The risk ID and title","The gap between inherent risk and residual risk","The date the entry was originally created","The name of the risk practitioner who logged the entry"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The gap between inherent risk and residual risk</strong> — comparing risk before controls (inherent) to risk after controls (residual) directly measures how much the existing controls are reducing exposure for that specific risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The risk ID and title</b>: this is an administrative reference field with no bearing on control effectiveness.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The date the entry was originally created</b>: creation date is a tracking detail, not a measure of control value.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The name of the risk practitioner who logged the entry</b>: authorship has no relationship to how effective the controls are.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-035","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"easy","q":"Which risk analysis approach relies on descriptive categories such as high, medium, and low rather than precise numeric values?","options":["Quantitative risk analysis","Monte Carlo simulation","Qualitative risk analysis","Actuarial loss-table analysis"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Qualitative risk analysis</strong> — this approach uses descriptive ratings and expert judgment rather than precise monetary or statistical figures.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Quantitative risk analysis</b>: this approach expresses likelihood and impact in numerical or monetary terms, the opposite of descriptive categories.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Monte Carlo simulation</b>: this is a specific quantitative modeling technique using statistical simulation, not descriptive ratings.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Actuarial loss-table analysis</b>: this is a specialized quantitative technique based on statistical loss data, not qualitative categories.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-036","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"med","q":"An organization with limited historical loss data needs a quick, broad risk assessment across many business units. Which analysis method is MOST appropriate?","options":["Pure quantitative analysis using Monte Carlo simulation","Actuarial analysis based on insurance industry loss tables","Full statistical regression modeling of historical incidents","Qualitative analysis using expert judgment and descriptive risk ratings"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Qualitative analysis using expert judgment and descriptive risk ratings</strong> — when data is scarce and speed/breadth matter, qualitative methods let experts rate likelihood and impact quickly without requiring extensive historical loss data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Pure quantitative analysis using Monte Carlo simulation</b>: this requires substantial data inputs and modeling effort that are impractical without historical data.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Actuarial analysis based on insurance industry loss tables</b>: this is specialized and resource-intensive, not typically used for a broad, rapid internal assessment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Full statistical regression modeling of historical incidents</b>: this depends on rich historical data sets that are explicitly unavailable in this scenario.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-037","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner uses a 5x5 heat-map matrix to rate risks by assigning numeric scores (1-5) to both likelihood and impact, then multiplying them for a composite score. This approach is BEST classified as:","options":["Semi-quantitative analysis","Pure quantitative analysis","Pure qualitative analysis with no numeric element","Actuarial analysis"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Semi-quantitative analysis</strong> — assigning numeric scores to qualitative categories and combining them for relative comparison, without deriving precise monetary values, is the defining characteristic of a semi-quantitative approach.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Pure quantitative analysis</b>: pure quantitative analysis produces precise monetary figures such as ALE, not a relative numeric score from a matrix.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Pure qualitative analysis with no numeric element</b>: the described approach explicitly uses numeric scores, which goes beyond purely descriptive ratings.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Actuarial analysis</b>: actuarial analysis relies on statistical loss-table data, not a simple likelihood-times-impact matrix score.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-038","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"med","q":"A key limitation of qualitative risk analysis, compared to quantitative analysis, is that it:","options":["Cannot be performed without extensive historical loss data","Introduces subjectivity and may make cost-benefit comparisons across risks less precise","Always takes longer to complete than quantitative analysis","Cannot be used for information technology risk at all"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Introduces subjectivity and may make cost-benefit comparisons across risks less precise</strong> — because qualitative analysis relies on descriptive ratings and expert judgment rather than precise figures, it is inherently more subjective and less suited to fine-grained financial comparisons.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Cannot be performed without extensive historical loss data</b>: qualitative analysis is actually preferred precisely because it does not require extensive historical data.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Always takes longer to complete than quantitative analysis</b>: qualitative analysis is generally faster, not slower, than rigorous quantitative modeling.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Cannot be used for information technology risk at all</b>: qualitative analysis is widely and appropriately used for IT risk assessment.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-039","domain":2,"obj":"2B5","diff":"easy","q":"A risk has an SLE of $45,000 and an ARO of 2 (expected twice per year). What is the ALE?","options":["$45,000","$22,500","$90,000","$135,000"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>$90,000</strong> — ALE = SLE x ARO = $45,000 x 2 = $90,000.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>$45,000</b>: this is only the SLE, ignoring the frequency of occurrence.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$22,500</b>: results from dividing rather than multiplying SLE by ARO.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$135,000</b>: does not correspond to the correct multiplication of the given SLE and ARO.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-040","domain":2,"obj":"2B5","diff":"med","q":"An asset valued at $250,000 has an exposure factor of 60% for a specific threat expected to occur once every 4 years. What is the ALE?","options":["$150,000","$60,000","$25,000","$37,500"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>$37,500</strong> — SLE = AV x EF = $250,000 x 0.60 = $150,000. ARO = 1/4 = 0.25. ALE = SLE x ARO = $150,000 x 0.25 = $37,500.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>$150,000</b>: this is the SLE value only, without applying the annualized rate of occurrence.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$60,000</b>: does not correspond to the correct multiplication of SLE and ARO using the given figures.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$25,000</b>: results from an incorrect ARO of 1/6 rather than the correct 0.25.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-041","domain":2,"obj":"2B5","diff":"hard","q":"A control costing $15,000 per year is expected to reduce ALE from $70,000 to $40,000. What is the ROSI?","options":["100%","50%","200%","467%"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>100%</strong> — ROSI = (Risk reduction - Cost of control) / Cost of control = (($70,000 - $40,000) - $15,000) / $15,000 = $15,000 / $15,000 = 100%.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>50%</b>: does not match the correct net-benefit-over-cost calculation using the figures given.</span> <span class='qd'><b>200%</b>: represents the gross benefit-to-cost ratio ($30,000/$15,000) without subtracting appropriately to form net ROSI.</span> <span class='qd'><b>467%</b>: does not correspond to any correct calculation using the given figures.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-042","domain":2,"obj":"2B5","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the MOST important prerequisite for performing meaningful quantitative risk analysis using ALE?","options":["A board-approved risk appetite statement","Reasonably reliable data on asset value, exposure factor, and frequency of occurrence","A completed penetration test report","A fully staffed security operations center"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Reasonably reliable data on asset value, exposure factor, and frequency of occurrence</strong> — quantitative analysis depends on credible inputs for AV, EF, and ARO; without reasonably reliable data, the resulting SLE and ALE figures are not meaningful.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A board-approved risk appetite statement</b>: appetite informs treatment decisions after analysis but is not itself an input to the ALE calculation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A completed penetration test report</b>: a penetration test may inform likelihood estimates but is not a strict prerequisite for quantitative analysis generally.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A fully staffed security operations center</b>: staffing levels are an operational resource unrelated to the data needed for ALE calculation.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-043","domain":2,"obj":"2B5","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner calculates an ALE of $500,000 for a risk, but stakeholders question the exposure factor used because it was based on a single analyst's estimate with no supporting data. What is the MOST appropriate response?","options":["Present the ALE figure as final and definitive regardless of the concern","Discard quantitative analysis entirely and switch to a purely qualitative rating","Validate and refine the exposure factor using additional data sources or expert consensus before relying on the ALE for decision-making","Increase the exposure factor arbitrarily to be conservative"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Validate and refine the exposure factor using additional data sources or expert consensus before relying on the ALE for decision-making</strong> — since quantitative outputs are only as credible as their inputs, an unsupported exposure factor should be validated or refined using better data or structured expert consensus before the ALE is used to drive decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Present the ALE figure as final and definitive regardless of the concern</b>: presenting an unvalidated figure as definitive risks misleading decision-makers.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Discard quantitative analysis entirely and switch to a purely qualitative rating</b>: abandoning quantitative analysis is an overreaction when the actual issue is a single unvalidated input.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increase the exposure factor arbitrarily to be conservative</b>: arbitrarily adjusting the figure without justification introduces new inaccuracy rather than resolving the original concern.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-044","domain":2,"obj":"2B6","diff":"easy","q":"Which term BEST describes the level of risk that exists before any controls are applied?","options":["Residual risk","Control risk","Risk tolerance","Inherent risk"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Inherent risk</strong> — this is the raw level of risk associated with an asset or activity assuming no controls are in place to reduce it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Residual risk</b>: this is the risk remaining after controls have been applied, the opposite of inherent risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Control risk</b>: this refers to the possibility that a control fails to operate as intended, a distinct concept.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Risk tolerance</b>: this describes the acceptable variation around an objective, unrelated to the pre-control risk level.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-045","domain":2,"obj":"2B6","diff":"med","q":"After implementing new access controls, a risk practitioner wants to determine the risk that remains for a given system. This remaining risk is BEST known as:","options":["Residual risk","Inherent risk","Aggregate risk","Control risk"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Residual risk</strong> — this is the risk that remains after controls have been applied to reduce the inherent risk, and it must be compared against risk tolerance to decide if further treatment is needed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Inherent risk</b>: this is the level of risk before any controls are applied, the opposite of what is being asked.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Aggregate risk</b>: this refers to combined risk across multiple sources or systems, not the specific post-control remainder for one risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Control risk</b>: this refers to the possibility that a control itself fails to operate as intended, a related but distinct concept.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-046","domain":2,"obj":"2B6","diff":"hard","q":"Residual risk for a critical application remains above the organization's defined risk tolerance even after compensating controls were implemented. What should the risk practitioner do NEXT?","options":["Close the risk in the register since controls were already implemented","Present the residual risk to the appropriate risk owner for a formal decision on further treatment or documented acceptance","Unilaterally accept the risk to save time","Remove the application from production without consulting stakeholders"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Present the residual risk to the appropriate risk owner for a formal decision on further treatment or documented acceptance</strong> — when residual risk exceeds tolerance, the accountable risk owner must decide whether to apply further treatment or formally accept the risk; this decision is outside the practitioner's sole authority.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Close the risk in the register since controls were already implemented</b>: closing the risk while it still exceeds tolerance misrepresents the organization's actual exposure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Unilaterally accept the risk to save time</b>: acceptance decisions exceeding tolerance require authority the practitioner typically does not hold alone.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Remove the application from production without consulting stakeholders</b>: an operational decision of this magnitude requires business consultation, not unilateral action.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-047","domain":2,"obj":"2B6","diff":"med","q":"An organization's inherent risk for a data exposure scenario is rated \"very high,\" but after strong encryption and access controls are applied, residual risk drops to \"low.\" What does this gap BEST demonstrate?","options":["The risk should be removed from the register since it is now low","The inherent risk rating was calculated incorrectly","The existing controls are providing significant risk reduction value","No further monitoring of this risk is required going forward"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The existing controls are providing significant risk reduction value</strong> — a large gap between inherent and residual risk directly demonstrates that the applied controls are substantially reducing exposure for that risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The risk should be removed from the register since it is now low</b>: a low residual rating still warrants ongoing tracking, since controls could later fail or degrade.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The inherent risk rating was calculated incorrectly</b>: a large gap does not indicate an error; it reflects the actual effect of strong controls.</span> <span class='qd'><b>No further monitoring of this risk is required going forward</b>: even low residual risks require periodic monitoring since conditions and controls can change.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-048","domain":2,"obj":"2B6","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following would MOST directly cause residual risk to increase without any change in the underlying threat or asset value?","options":["The organization publishes a new risk appetite statement","The risk practitioner updates the risk register's formatting","A new risk practitioner is assigned to the risk register","A previously effective control fails or is disabled"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A previously effective control fails or is disabled</strong> — since residual risk reflects risk after controls, the failure or removal of a control directly increases residual risk even though the threat and asset value have not changed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization publishes a new risk appetite statement</b>: appetite is a decision-making threshold and does not itself change the actual residual risk level.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The risk practitioner updates the risk register's formatting</b>: formatting changes are cosmetic and have no bearing on actual risk levels.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A new risk practitioner is assigned to the risk register</b>: a change in personnel managing the register does not itself alter residual risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-049","domain":2,"obj":"2B7","diff":"med","q":"Which visualization tool is MOST commonly used to communicate relative risk priority by plotting likelihood against impact?","options":["A risk heat map","A network topology diagram","A Gantt chart","An organizational chart"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A risk heat map</strong> — this visualization plots likelihood on one axis and impact on the other, using color coding to quickly communicate relative risk priority to stakeholders.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A network topology diagram</b>: this depicts technical network architecture, not risk likelihood and impact.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A Gantt chart</b>: this is a project scheduling tool showing timelines and dependencies, unrelated to risk prioritization.</span> <span class='qd'><b>An organizational chart</b>: this depicts reporting structure and roles, not risk levels.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-050","domain":2,"obj":"2B7","diff":"hard","q":"A risk heat map shows two risks both landing in the same \"high\" color-coded cell (likelihood: high, impact: high). Stakeholders ask which of the two should be treated first. What is the BEST approach to resolve this?","options":["Treat both risks in strict alphabetical order of their titles","Apply more granular criteria, such as underlying numeric scores, cost of treatment, or velocity of onset, to differentiate priority within the same cell","Flip a coin, since both risks occupy the same heat-map cell","Ignore both risks since the heat map cannot distinguish them further"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Apply more granular criteria, such as underlying numeric scores, cost of treatment, or velocity of onset, to differentiate priority within the same cell</strong> — a heat map is a coarse visualization; when risks land in the same cell, practitioners should drill into finer-grained data (exact scores, speed of onset, treatment cost/feasibility) to establish a defensible priority order.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Treat both risks in strict alphabetical order of their titles</b>: alphabetical ordering has no relationship to actual risk severity or urgency.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Flip a coin, since both risks occupy the same heat-map cell</b>: random selection ignores available information that could meaningfully differentiate the risks.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore both risks since the heat map cannot distinguish them further</b>: ignoring both risks abandons the goal of prioritization entirely rather than refining the analysis.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-051","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST distinguishes a threat from a vulnerability during risk identification?","options":["A threat is a weakness that can be exploited, while a vulnerability is the entity that exploits it","There is no practical distinction between the two terms for risk purposes","A threat is a potential cause of an unwanted event, while a vulnerability is a weakness that could be exploited by that threat","A vulnerability always results in a loss, while a threat never does"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A threat is a potential cause of an unwanted event, while a vulnerability is a weakness that could be exploited by that threat</strong> — a threat is the potential source of harm, whereas a vulnerability is the weakness in an asset or control that the threat could exploit to cause harm.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A threat is a weakness that can be exploited, while a vulnerability is the entity that exploits it</b>: this reverses the correct definitions of the two terms.</span> <span class='qd'><b>There is no practical distinction between the two terms for risk purposes</b>: the distinction is fundamental to risk analysis, since risk arises only from the pairing of the two.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A vulnerability always results in a loss, while a threat never does</b>: neither a vulnerability nor a threat alone guarantees a loss; loss requires both combined with exploitation.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-052","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of a vulnerability rather than a threat?","options":["A disgruntled employee","A hurricane","A malicious external attacker","An unpatched operating system"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>An unpatched operating system</strong> — a missing patch is a weakness in the system that could be exploited, making it a vulnerability rather than a source of harm itself.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A disgruntled employee</b>: this represents a potential source of harm (an insider threat actor), not a weakness.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A hurricane</b>: this is an environmental/natural threat source, not a system weakness.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A malicious external attacker</b>: this represents a threat actor, not a vulnerability.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-053","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is updating the organization's threat landscape assessment. Which source combination would BEST support a current and relevant view of applicable threats?","options":["Sector-specific information-sharing groups, vendor advisories, and internal incident telemetry filtered for relevance to the organization's assets","Only the personal social media feed of the risk practitioner","A single five-year-old industry report","Rumors circulated informally among staff at a conference"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Sector-specific information-sharing groups, vendor advisories, and internal incident telemetry filtered for relevance to the organization's assets</strong> — combining structured external intelligence sources with internal telemetry, then filtering for actual relevance, produces a current and actionable threat landscape view.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Only the personal social media feed of the risk practitioner</b>: an individual's informal social feed is not a reliable or comprehensive intelligence source.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A single five-year-old industry report</b>: outdated information does not reflect the current threat landscape.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Rumors circulated informally among staff at a conference</b>: unverified informal rumors are not a credible basis for threat assessment.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-054","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner observes that the organization treats every new threat headline with an urgent new risk-register entry and a hastily approved control, regardless of actual relevance. This behavior is BEST described as:","options":["Effective threat intelligence triage","Threat chasing, which burns credibility and resources on low-relevance items while starving attention from already-known unmitigated risks","A best-practice model for threat landscape management","Threat fatigue"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Threat chasing, which burns credibility and resources on low-relevance items while starving attention from already-known unmitigated risks</strong> — reacting to every headline without assessing relevance wastes resources and distracts from risks that are already known and still unaddressed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Effective threat intelligence triage</b>: genuine triage involves assessing relevance before acting, which is precisely what is missing in this scenario.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A best-practice model for threat landscape management</b>: reacting to every headline without filtering is the opposite of a disciplined, mature practice.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Threat fatigue</b>: fatigue describes ignoring threats due to volume, which is the opposite behavior from over-reacting to every one.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-055","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following vulnerability categories is MOST often overlooked by organizations that equate vulnerability management solely with patch management?","options":["Missing operating system patches","Outdated antivirus signature files","Process and architectural vulnerabilities, such as a flat network with no segmentation","Unpatched web server software"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Process and architectural vulnerabilities, such as a flat network with no segmentation</strong> — organizations that narrowly define vulnerability management as patching often miss structural weaknesses in process design and network architecture that are just as exploitable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Missing operating system patches</b>: this is precisely the technical category that patch-focused programs already address.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Outdated antivirus signature files</b>: this is also a technical, patch-adjacent vulnerability already captured by narrow patch-focused programs.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Unpatched web server software</b>: this too falls squarely within the technical patching scope already covered by such programs.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-056","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner finds a legacy system with a known critical vulnerability, but it is fully isolated on a segmented network with no path to sensitive data or the internet. How should this finding BEST be treated?","options":["Treat it identically to an internet-facing critical vulnerability requiring emergency patching within 24 hours","Remove it from all tracking since isolation makes it irrelevant","Immediately decommission the system without further analysis","Document it as an accepted, monitored exposure supported by the compensating segmentation control, rather than an active unmitigated deficiency"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Document it as an accepted, monitored exposure supported by the compensating segmentation control, rather than an active unmitigated deficiency</strong> — a vulnerability that exists alongside an effective compensating control reduces actual residual risk to an acceptable level, and this context should be documented and monitored rather than treated with the same urgency as an exposed system.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Treat it identically to an internet-facing critical vulnerability requiring emergency patching within 24 hours</b>: applying identical urgency ignores the very different exposure and actual risk level created by segmentation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Remove it from all tracking since isolation makes it irrelevant</b>: the vulnerability still exists and should remain tracked and monitored in case conditions change.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately decommission the system without further analysis</b>: decommissioning without analysis is a disproportionate action not justified by the facts presented.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-057","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"med","q":"A risk scenario states: \"An external attacker exploits an unpatched VPN concentrator to access the patient-scheduling system, causing 3-5 days of unavailability and regulatory exposure.\" Which risk component is represented by \"an unpatched VPN concentrator\"?","options":["The vulnerability","The threat","The asset","The impact"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The vulnerability</strong> — the unpatched VPN concentrator is the exploitable weakness that the attacker leverages, making it the vulnerability component of the scenario.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The threat</b>: the external attacker is the threat source in this scenario, not the unpatched component itself.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The asset</b>: the patient-scheduling system is the asset at risk, not the VPN concentrator's unpatched state.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The impact</b>: the 3-5 days of unavailability and regulatory exposure represent the impact, not the vulnerability.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-058","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"hard","q":"During scenario development, a risk practitioner must decide the appropriate level of specificity for a new scenario involving a third-party payroll provider. Which level of detail is MOST appropriate?","options":["So specific that the scenario becomes invalid if the provider changes its office location","Specific enough to name the provider, the exploitable condition, and the business consequence, but general enough to remain useful if minor provider details change","So vague that it could apply to any vendor in any industry","Limited strictly to the technical CVE identifiers involved"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Specific enough to name the provider, the exploitable condition, and the business consequence, but general enough to remain useful if minor provider details change</strong> — effective scenarios balance specificity for analyzability with enough durability that trivial changes do not immediately invalidate the entry.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>So specific that the scenario becomes invalid if the provider changes its office location</b>: over-specifying irrelevant details makes the scenario fragile and easily outdated.</span> <span class='qd'><b>So vague that it could apply to any vendor in any industry</b>: excessive vagueness prevents meaningful likelihood and impact analysis.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Limited strictly to the technical CVE identifiers involved</b>: focusing only on technical identifiers omits the business context needed for risk evaluation.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-059","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"easy","q":"Which risk identification technique involves examining a business process end to end to find where controls are weak or missing?","options":["Automated vulnerability scanning","Financial ratio analysis","Process walkthroughs","Firewall rule auditing"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Process walkthroughs</strong> — this technique traces a business process from start to finish to identify points where controls are absent, weak, or bypassed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Automated vulnerability scanning</b>: this is a technical scanning method targeting systems, not a process-tracing technique.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Financial ratio analysis</b>: this is a finance-specific analytical method unrelated to process control walkthroughs.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Firewall rule auditing</b>: this is a technical network control review, not an end-to-end process examination.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-060","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"med","q":"A new cloud-based HR system was deployed without ever appearing in a risk identification workshop, and a later configuration error exposed employee records. What is the BEST long-term fix?","options":["Perform a one-time cleanup of this single system's configuration","Require the HR department to personally review all future configurations","Add the vendor to a blocklist for future projects","Integrate a mandatory risk-identification gate into the project and change-management lifecycle so new initiatives are routed through risk identification before go-live"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Integrate a mandatory risk-identification gate into the project and change-management lifecycle so new initiatives are routed through risk identification before go-live</strong> — the root cause was a broken identification process, not a one-off configuration mistake, so the durable fix is ensuring all new technology initiatives pass through risk identification before deployment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Perform a one-time cleanup of this single system's configuration</b>: fixing only this instance does not prevent the same identification gap from recurring with future systems.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Require the HR department to personally review all future configurations</b>: this places technical review responsibility on a business unit lacking the expertise, rather than fixing the process gate.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Add the vendor to a blocklist for future projects</b>: blocklisting the vendor does not address the systemic process failure that allowed any new system to bypass risk identification.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-061","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"med","q":"Which characteristic is MOST important for a metric to function effectively as a key risk indicator (KRI)?","options":["It must be measurable, relevant to a specific risk, and able to signal a change in risk level in time for action","It must be reported only annually to the board","It must be easy for a process owner to manipulate favorably","It must always be expressed strictly in monetary terms"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>It must be measurable, relevant to a specific risk, and able to signal a change in risk level in time for action</strong> — an effective KRI is quantifiable, tied to a meaningful risk, and timely enough that management can respond before the risk materializes into a loss.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It must be reported only annually to the board</b>: annual reporting is far too infrequent for a leading indicator meant to provide early warning.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It must be easy for a process owner to manipulate favorably</b>: a metric that can be easily manipulated undermines its reliability and integrity.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It must always be expressed strictly in monetary terms</b>: many effective KRIs, such as patch latency or failed login trends, are non-monetary yet highly effective.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-062","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner notices a chosen KRI (number of failed login attempts per day) has remained flat for two years despite significant changes in the threat landscape and user base growth. What is the MOST likely conclusion?","options":["The organization's risk level has genuinely remained completely unchanged","The KRI may no longer be sensitive or relevant enough to reflect actual changes in risk and should be reviewed or recalibrated","The KRI should be reported less frequently since it never changes","All other risk indicators should be discontinued as unnecessary"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The KRI may no longer be sensitive or relevant enough to reflect actual changes in risk and should be reviewed or recalibrated</strong> — a static metric despite known environmental changes suggests it has lost sensitivity or relevance, and effective KRIs must be periodically reviewed and recalibrated to remain meaningful.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization's risk level has genuinely remained completely unchanged</b>: given the stated changes, an unchanging metric more likely signals a flawed indicator than a static risk level.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The KRI should be reported less frequently since it never changes</b>: reducing reporting frequency does not address the underlying concern that the metric may be ineffective.</span> <span class='qd'><b>All other risk indicators should be discontinued as unnecessary</b>: this conclusion is unsupported and disproportionate to the observation about a single metric.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-063","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY input a business impact analysis (BIA) provides to risk assessment?","options":["The exact dollar value of every risk in the register","The organization's overall risk appetite statement","Criticality rankings and recovery time/point requirements for business processes, which inform impact ratings for related risk scenarios","A list of external threat actors relevant to the industry"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Criticality rankings and recovery time/point requirements for business processes, which inform impact ratings for related risk scenarios</strong> — the BIA identifies how critical each process is and how quickly it must be recovered, directly shaping how severe the impact rating should be for risks affecting that process.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The exact dollar value of every risk in the register</b>: precise dollar values come from quantitative analysis (SLE/ALE), not directly from the BIA.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization's overall risk appetite statement</b>: appetite is set by senior management as a strategic decision, separate from BIA outputs.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A list of external threat actors relevant to the industry</b>: threat actor identification comes from threat modeling and intelligence, not the BIA.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-064","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"hard","q":"A BIA identifies that the customer-facing order system has an MTD of 12 hours, but the current disaster recovery plan assumes a 20-hour recovery time. What is the MOST significant risk this discrepancy creates?","options":["The MTD figure must be immediately increased to 20 hours to match the DR plan","No risk exists as long as the RPO is met","The discrepancy is purely a documentation issue with no operational consequence","The organization could suffer unacceptable harm before recovery is even achieved, since the planned recovery time exceeds the maximum tolerable downtime"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The organization could suffer unacceptable harm before recovery is even achieved, since the planned recovery time exceeds the maximum tolerable downtime</strong> — when a recovery plan takes longer than the process's MTD, the business will cross the threshold of unacceptable harm before systems are even restored, representing a critical gap that must be addressed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The MTD figure must be immediately increased to 20 hours to match the DR plan</b>: silently relaxing the business-driven MTD to match technical capability bypasses proper business risk evaluation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>No risk exists as long as the RPO is met</b>: meeting the recovery point objective does not address the separate, significant downtime exposure created by the MTD gap.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The discrepancy is purely a documentation issue with no operational consequence</b>: this materially understates a real recovery-capability gap with direct business consequences.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-065","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"easy","q":"Who is generally MOST appropriate to serve as the owner of a specific business risk?","options":["The senior manager accountable for the business process or asset affected by the risk","The risk practitioner who logged the entry in the register","The internal audit director","The IT help desk supervisor"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The senior manager accountable for the business process or asset affected by the risk</strong> — risk ownership belongs to the business role with authority over the asset/process and accountability for outcomes, ensuring treatment decisions align with business priorities.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The risk practitioner who logged the entry in the register</b>: this role facilitates and documents the risk process but is not the accountable business owner.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The internal audit director</b>: audit provides independent assurance and should not own risks it must objectively assess.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The IT help desk supervisor</b>: this role operates at a tactical support level and lacks the authority to accept or treat business risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-066","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"med","q":"What is the KEY difference between a risk owner and a control owner?","options":["There is no meaningful difference; the terms are interchangeable","The risk owner is accountable for the risk outcome, while the control owner is responsible for operating and maintaining a specific control that treats the risk","The control owner sets organizational risk appetite, while the risk owner implements technical safeguards","The risk owner is always in IT, while the control owner is always in the business"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The risk owner is accountable for the risk outcome, while the control owner is responsible for operating and maintaining a specific control that treats the risk</strong> — one risk may be treated by multiple controls with different control owners, but overall accountability for the risk remains with the risk owner.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>There is no meaningful difference; the terms are interchangeable</b>: conflating the roles removes accountability clarity, which defeats the purpose of assigning ownership.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The control owner sets organizational risk appetite, while the risk owner implements technical safeguards</b>: this reverses the actual responsibilities of each role.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The risk owner is always in IT, while the control owner is always in the business</b>: ownership is determined by accountability and function, not a fixed departmental rule.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-067","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"hard","q":"A risk register lists \"IT department\" as the risk owner for a business process disruption risk affecting the finance function. What is the PRIMARY concern with this assignment?","options":["IT departments are never allowed to own any risk under any circumstances","This assignment guarantees the risk will be treated faster than any other assignment would","The listed owner lacks the business authority and accountability over the affected finance process, undermining meaningful risk decision-making","Listing a department instead of a named individual is always acceptable with no drawbacks"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The listed owner lacks the business authority and accountability over the affected finance process, undermining meaningful risk decision-making</strong> — an effective risk owner must have authority over the affected process or asset; assigning ownership to a department that does not control the business process weakens accountability and decision quality.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>IT departments are never allowed to own any risk under any circumstances</b>: IT can appropriately own risks tied to IT-controlled assets; the issue here is the mismatch with the finance process, not a blanket prohibition.</span> <span class='qd'><b>This assignment guarantees the risk will be treated faster than any other assignment would</b>: there is no basis for assuming faster treatment from a misaligned ownership assignment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Listing a department instead of a named individual is always acceptable with no drawbacks</b>: vague departmental ownership generally weakens, rather than strengthens, individual accountability.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-068","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is choosing between a purely qualitative and a purely quantitative risk analysis approach for a new enterprise resource planning (ERP) implementation. Which factor would MOST justify using a quantitative approach?","options":["The organization has no historical loss or frequency data available","The assessment must be completed within one business day","Stakeholders prefer simple high/medium/low ratings for a board presentation","Management requires a precise dollar-based cost-benefit justification for a large capital investment in controls"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Management requires a precise dollar-based cost-benefit justification for a large capital investment in controls</strong> — quantitative analysis is best suited when a specific monetary justification, such as calculating ALE and ROSI, is required to support a capital expenditure decision.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization has no historical loss or frequency data available</b>: lack of reliable data actually favors a qualitative approach, since quantitative analysis depends on solid data inputs.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The assessment must be completed within one business day</b>: quantitative analysis is typically more time- and data-intensive, making qualitative analysis faster under tight deadlines.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Stakeholders prefer simple high/medium/low ratings for a board presentation</b>: a preference for simple descriptive ratings points toward qualitative analysis, not quantitative.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-069","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes a semi-quantitative risk analysis approach?","options":["Assigning numeric scores or weighted rankings to qualitative categories to allow relative comparison without precise monetary values","Using only descriptive terms such as high, medium, and low with no numeric scoring at all","Calculating exact monetary loss figures using verified historical data exclusively","Relying solely on regulatory checklists without any risk scoring"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Assigning numeric scores or weighted rankings to qualitative categories to allow relative comparison without precise monetary values</strong> — semi-quantitative analysis blends the descriptive nature of qualitative methods with numeric scoring or weighting, enabling relative comparison without requiring precise monetary data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Using only descriptive terms such as high, medium, and low with no numeric scoring at all</b>: this describes purely qualitative analysis, not the semi-quantitative approach.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Calculating exact monetary loss figures using verified historical data exclusively</b>: this describes purely quantitative analysis.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Relying solely on regulatory checklists without any risk scoring</b>: a compliance checklist approach does not constitute risk analysis at all.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-070","domain":2,"obj":"2B5","diff":"easy","q":"Which risk analysis approach relies on numerical values such as monetary loss and probability percentages?","options":["Qualitative risk analysis","Quantitative risk analysis","Delphi technique alone","Heat-map scoring only"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Quantitative risk analysis</strong> — this approach expresses likelihood and impact in numerical/monetary terms (e.g., ALE, ROSI), enabling direct cost-benefit comparisons.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Qualitative risk analysis</b>: this approach uses descriptive categories such as high/medium/low rather than precise numeric values.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delphi technique alone</b>: this is a structured method for gathering expert consensus and can support either qualitative or quantitative analysis, but is not itself the numerical approach.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Heat-map scoring only</b>: heat maps typically visualize qualitative or semi-quantitative scores, not precise monetary figures.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-071","domain":2,"obj":"2B5","diff":"med","q":"An organization values a customer database at $1,500,000. A ransomware attack is estimated to cause a 40% loss of value and is expected to occur once every three years. What is the ALE?","options":["$600,000","$450,000","$200,000","$150,000"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>$200,000</strong> — SLE = AV x EF = $1,500,000 x 0.40 = $600,000. ARO = 1/3 = 0.333. ALE = SLE x ARO = $600,000 x 0.333 ≈ $200,000.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>$600,000</b>: this is the SLE only, without applying the annualized rate of occurrence.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$450,000</b>: does not result from correctly multiplying the given SLE and ARO.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$150,000</b>: results from an incorrect exposure factor calculation rather than the given 40%.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-072","domain":2,"obj":"2B5","diff":"hard","q":"A control costing $25,000 per year is expected to reduce ALE from $120,000 to $70,000. What is the ROSI?","options":["42%","200%","58%","100%"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>100%</strong> — ROSI = (Risk reduction - Cost of control) / Cost of control = (($120,000 - $70,000) - $25,000) / $25,000 = $25,000 / $25,000 = 100%.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>42%</b>: does not match the correct net-benefit-over-cost calculation using the figures given.</span> <span class='qd'><b>200%</b>: represents the gross benefit-to-cost ratio ($50,000/$25,000) without subtracting appropriately to form net ROSI.</span> <span class='qd'><b>58%</b>: does not correspond to any correct calculation using the given figures.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-073","domain":2,"obj":"2B6","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY reason for conducting periodic reassessment of previously identified and treated risks?","options":["To confirm that the risk environment, controls, and business context have not changed in ways that affect the risk's current level or treatment adequacy","To satisfy a fixed annual audit requirement only","To reduce the total number of entries in the risk register","To eliminate the need for new risk assessments on future projects"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>To confirm that the risk environment, controls, and business context have not changed in ways that affect the risk's current level or treatment adequacy</strong> — risks are dynamic; periodic reassessment ensures that changes in threats, vulnerabilities, controls, or business context are reflected so treatment decisions remain appropriate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To satisfy a fixed annual audit requirement only</b>: while audits may prompt review, the underlying purpose is maintaining an accurate and current risk picture, not merely satisfying a compliance calendar.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To reduce the total number of entries in the risk register</b>: reassessment aims for accuracy, not artificially reducing the register's size.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To eliminate the need for new risk assessments on future projects</b>: reassessing existing risks does not replace the need to assess risk on new initiatives.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-074","domain":2,"obj":"2B6","diff":"easy","q":"An organization's risk appetite statement allows for a maximum of 4 hours of unplanned downtime per critical system per quarter. This specific, measurable threshold is BEST described as an example of:","options":["Risk appetite","Risk tolerance","Residual risk","Inherent risk"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Risk tolerance</strong> — tolerance is the specific, measurable acceptable deviation from an objective (such as an uptime target), operationalizing the broader risk appetite into actionable thresholds.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Risk appetite</b>: this is the broader, strategic-level statement of overall willingness to accept risk, not the specific numeric threshold.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Residual risk</b>: this is the risk remaining after controls are applied, a different measurement altogether.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Inherent risk</b>: this is the risk level before controls are considered, unrelated to a tolerance threshold.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-075","domain":2,"obj":"2B7","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is preparing a report for the risk committee showing which risks require immediate attention. Which technique BEST supports rapid, visual prioritization across dozens of risks?","options":["Listing all risks in the order they were originally identified","Sorting risks alphabetically by risk title","Plotting risks on a heat map by likelihood and impact, then ranking within color bands using underlying numeric scores","Presenting each risk in a separate, unranked slide with no comparison"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Plotting risks on a heat map by likelihood and impact, then ranking within color bands using underlying numeric scores</strong> — this combines a fast visual overview with a defensible, granular ranking mechanism for risks that fall into the same color band, supporting efficient prioritization across many risks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Listing all risks in the order they were originally identified</b>: identification order has no relationship to actual severity or urgency.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Sorting risks alphabetically by risk title</b>: alphabetical sorting provides no meaningful prioritization insight.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Presenting each risk in a separate, unranked slide with no comparison</b>: this approach fails to support rapid comparison or prioritization across risks.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-076","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"easy","q":"A risk practitioner is briefing new analysts on loss-event classification. Which loss-event type is represented by a distributed denial-of-service attack that takes an online banking portal offline for six hours?","options":["Availability","Confidentiality","Integrity","Compliance"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Availability</strong> — preventing legitimate users from accessing a system or service for a period of time is the defining feature of an availability loss event.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality</b>: nothing indicates data was disclosed to an unauthorized party.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Integrity</b>: no data was altered or corrupted in this scenario.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Compliance</b>: while a prolonged outage might eventually raise regulatory questions, the direct, primary loss-event type here is availability.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-077","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following threat actor categories is MOST likely to use long-dwell-time intrusions and zero-day exploits in pursuit of espionage or strategic disruption?","options":["Script kiddies acting opportunistically","Nation-state actors","Hacktivists seeking publicity","Competitors engaged in casual benchmarking"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Nation-state actors</strong> — these actors are typically well-resourced and patient, favoring stealthy, long-term intrusions and advanced exploits to achieve espionage or strategic disruption objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Script kiddies acting opportunistically</b>: this group typically lacks the sophistication and patience for long-dwell-time, zero-day-driven campaigns.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Hacktivists seeking publicity</b>: this group favors visible, disruptive actions such as defacement, not quiet, prolonged espionage.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Competitors engaged in casual benchmarking</b>: casual benchmarking is not a threat activity at all, let alone one involving zero-day exploits.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-078","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner finds that a documented control expected to review privileged access quarterly has not actually been performed for three consecutive quarters, even though the control's design is sound. This is BEST classified as which type of deficiency?","options":["A design flaw in the control","An operating gap, since the control is designed adequately but not performed as intended","A vulnerability with no associated control expected at all","An accepted risk requiring no further action"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>An operating gap, since the control is designed adequately but not performed as intended</strong> — the control's design is sound, but it is simply not being executed, which is precisely what defines an operating gap rather than a design problem.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A design flaw in the control</b>: a design flaw would mean the control could not achieve its objective even if performed, which is not the case here.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A vulnerability with no associated control expected at all</b>: a control is explicitly expected and documented, so this is not a design gap with no control at all.</span> <span class='qd'><b>An accepted risk requiring no further action</b>: nothing indicates management formally accepted this lapse; it is an unaddressed deficiency.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-079","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is developing a risk scenario for a payment-processing platform. Which of the following elements, if missing, would MOST undermine the scenario's usefulness for risk evaluation?","options":["The specific business impact or consequence of the scenario occurring","The font used to format the scenario document","The name of the risk practitioner who wrote the scenario","The color scheme of the risk register template"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The specific business impact or consequence of the scenario occurring</strong> — without a defined impact, the scenario cannot be evaluated for severity or prioritized against other risks, undermining its core purpose.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The font used to format the scenario document</b>: formatting has no bearing on the scenario's analytical usefulness.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The name of the risk practitioner who wrote the scenario</b>: authorship does not affect whether the scenario can be evaluated.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The color scheme of the risk register template</b>: visual styling is cosmetic and irrelevant to the scenario's substance.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-080","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"easy","q":"Which risk identification source is MOST useful for surfacing risks that have already materialized as near-misses within the organization?","options":["Historical incident and near-miss data","The organization's annual holiday calendar","A competitor's marketing brochure","A generic industry checklist with no organizational context"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Historical incident and near-miss data</strong> — reviewing past incidents and near-misses directly surfaces risks that have already shown themselves to be plausible within the organization's own environment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization's annual holiday calendar</b>: this has no relevance to identifying risks or near-misses.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A competitor's marketing brochure</b>: promotional material from a competitor provides no insight into the organization's own incident history.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A generic industry checklist with no organizational context</b>: a context-free checklist may miss risks specific to the organization's actual history and environment.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-081","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"med","q":"An organization's risk assessment methodology defines impact solely in terms of direct financial loss, ignoring reputational and regulatory consequences. What is the MOST significant limitation of this approach?","options":["Risks with severe non-financial consequences may be understated or overlooked in prioritization","The methodology will automatically overstate every risk's likelihood","The organization will no longer need a risk register","Financial impact is irrelevant to any risk assessment"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Risks with severe non-financial consequences may be understated or overlooked in prioritization</strong> — a narrow, purely financial definition of impact can miss risks whose primary damage is reputational, regulatory, or operational rather than a direct monetary loss, skewing prioritization.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The methodology will automatically overstate every risk's likelihood</b>: the described gap concerns impact criteria, not likelihood estimation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization will no longer need a risk register</b>: a narrow impact definition does not eliminate the need for a risk register.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Financial impact is irrelevant to any risk assessment</b>: financial impact remains a legitimate and important dimension; the issue is that it should not be the only one considered.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-082","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"hard","q":"A BIA for a critical trading platform determines an MTD of 2 hours, but the current architecture has no failover capability and historically takes 6 hours to restore after an outage. What is the MOST appropriate immediate step for the risk practitioner?","options":["Escalate the gap between MTD and actual recovery capability to the risk owner and business continuity stakeholders for a resourcing or redesign decision","Change the BIA's MTD figure to 6 hours to match current capability","Ignore the gap since the platform has not failed recently","Wait until the next annual BIA cycle to address the discrepancy"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Escalate the gap between MTD and actual recovery capability to the risk owner and business continuity stakeholders for a resourcing or redesign decision</strong> — a recovery capability that falls well short of the business-defined MTD is a significant risk that must be escalated promptly for a funded remediation or formal risk-acceptance decision, not deferred or quietly adjusted.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Change the BIA's MTD figure to 6 hours to match current capability</b>: silently relaxing the business-driven MTD to match technical limitations bypasses proper business risk evaluation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the gap since the platform has not failed recently</b>: absence of a recent failure does not reduce the actual exposure represented by the capability gap.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Wait until the next annual BIA cycle to address the discrepancy</b>: a gap of this magnitude on a critical platform warrants prompt escalation, not a deferred annual review.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-083","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"easy","q":"An asset has an asset value (AV) of $600,000 and an exposure factor (EF) of 50% for a specific threat. What is the single loss expectancy (SLE)?","options":["$300,000","$600,000","$150,000","$50,000"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>$300,000</strong> — SLE = AV x EF = $600,000 x 0.50 = $300,000.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>$600,000</b>: this is the full asset value, ignoring the exposure factor entirely.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$150,000</b>: results from an incorrect exposure factor (25%) rather than the given 50%.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$50,000</b>: does not correspond to the correct multiplication of the given AV and EF.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-084","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"med","q":"A newly appointed risk practitioner inherits a risk register where several entries list no risk owner at all. What is the MOST appropriate FIRST step?","options":["Delete the unowned entries since they cannot be actioned","Work with senior management to assign an accountable owner with authority over each affected process or asset","Assign the risk practitioner as owner of all unowned entries","Leave the entries unowned until the next audit cycle flags them"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Work with senior management to assign an accountable owner with authority over each affected process or asset</strong> — every risk needs an accountable owner with the authority to make treatment decisions, so the immediate priority is closing this ownership gap through proper business engagement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delete the unowned entries since they cannot be actioned</b>: deleting valid risks because they lack an owner removes visibility into real exposure rather than fixing the gap.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Assign the risk practitioner as owner of all unowned entries</b>: the practitioner typically lacks the business authority required to make risk acceptance and treatment decisions for these risks.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Leave the entries unowned until the next audit cycle flags them</b>: waiting passively for an audit to surface the gap delays a fix that should happen proactively.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-085","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"hard","q":"A risk committee wants to compare the relative severity of fifty distinct operational risks quickly, without investing in a full quantitative model for each one. Which analysis approach BEST fits this need?","options":["A full Monte Carlo simulation for every individual risk","A semi-quantitative scoring model using weighted numeric ratings for likelihood and impact","An actuarial loss-table analysis requiring years of claims data","A purely narrative description with no scoring for each risk"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A semi-quantitative scoring model using weighted numeric ratings for likelihood and impact</strong> — this approach enables fast, relative comparison across many risks using consistent numeric criteria, without the time and data burden of full quantitative modeling for each one.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A full Monte Carlo simulation for every individual risk</b>: running detailed simulations for fifty risks would be far too time- and data-intensive for this need.</span> <span class='qd'><b>An actuarial loss-table analysis requiring years of claims data</b>: this specialized technique requires extensive historical data not readily available for rapid comparison.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A purely narrative description with no scoring for each risk</b>: without any scoring, relative comparison across fifty risks becomes impractical.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-086","domain":2,"obj":"2B5","diff":"med","q":"An asset valued at $800,000 has an exposure factor of 30% for a specific threat expected to occur once every two years. What is the ALE?","options":["$240,000","$120,000","$80,000","$400,000"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>$120,000</strong> — SLE = AV x EF = $800,000 x 0.30 = $240,000. ARO = 1/2 = 0.5. ALE = SLE x ARO = $240,000 x 0.5 = $120,000.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>$240,000</b>: this is the SLE value only, without applying the annualized rate of occurrence.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$80,000</b>: does not correspond to the correct multiplication of SLE and ARO using the given figures.</span> <span class='qd'><b>$400,000</b>: does not result from a correct application of the given exposure factor and frequency.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-087","domain":2,"obj":"2B5","diff":"hard","q":"A control costing $18,000 per year is expected to reduce ALE from $60,000 to $35,000. What is the ROSI?","options":["139%","39%","72%","61%"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>39%</strong> — ROSI = (Risk reduction - Cost of control) / Cost of control = (($60,000 - $35,000) - $18,000) / $18,000 = $7,000 / $18,000 ≈ 39%.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>139%</b>: represents the gross benefit-to-cost ratio ($25,000/$18,000) without subtracting appropriately to form net ROSI.</span> <span class='qd'><b>72%</b>: does not match the correct net-benefit-over-cost calculation using the figures given.</span> <span class='qd'><b>61%</b>: does not correspond to any correct calculation using the given figures.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-088","domain":2,"obj":"2B6","diff":"easy","q":"A risk practitioner reports that inherent risk for a data-exposure scenario is \"very high\" while residual risk, after controls, is \"low.\" What does the SIZE of this gap primarily indicate?","options":["That the inherent risk rating must have been calculated in error","That no further monitoring of the risk is required","How much risk reduction value the current controls are providing","That the risk should be deleted from the register entirely"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>How much risk reduction value the current controls are providing</strong> — the size of the gap between inherent and residual risk is a direct measure of how effectively existing controls are reducing exposure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>That the inherent risk rating must have been calculated in error</b>: a large gap reflects strong controls, not a calculation mistake.</span> <span class='qd'><b>That no further monitoring of the risk is required</b>: even a low residual rating still requires ongoing monitoring in case controls degrade.</span> <span class='qd'><b>That the risk should be deleted from the register entirely</b>: a risk with low residual exposure should still remain tracked, not be removed.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-089","domain":2,"obj":"2B7","diff":"med","q":"On a standard risk heat map with likelihood and impact axes ranging from 1 (low) to 5 (high), which cell would generally represent the HIGHEST priority for treatment?","options":["Likelihood 1, Impact 1","Likelihood 5, Impact 1","Likelihood 5, Impact 5","Likelihood 1, Impact 5"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Likelihood 5, Impact 5</strong> — the cell combining the highest likelihood and highest impact represents the greatest overall risk exposure and therefore the highest treatment priority.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Likelihood 1, Impact 1</b>: this represents the lowest overall exposure and lowest treatment priority, the opposite of what is asked.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Likelihood 5, Impact 1</b>: a frequent but low-impact risk generally warrants lower priority than one that is both frequent and severe.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Likelihood 1, Impact 5</b>: a rare but severe risk still generally ranks below a risk that is both highly likely and highly severe.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-090","domain":2,"obj":"2A1","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner categorizes a data center power failure caused by an aging UPS system as which type of loss event?","options":["Confidentiality loss due to unauthorized disclosure","Integrity loss due to malicious tampering","Availability loss due to infrastructure failure","Compliance loss due to a missed regulatory filing"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Availability loss due to infrastructure failure</strong> — a power failure that disrupts system access due to aging infrastructure is a textbook availability loss event driven by a technical/infrastructure cause rather than malice or disclosure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality loss due to unauthorized disclosure</b>: no data disclosure is described in this scenario.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Integrity loss due to malicious tampering</b>: no data alteration or malicious activity is involved here.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Compliance loss due to a missed regulatory filing</b>: no regulatory filing or deadline is mentioned in this scenario.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-091","domain":2,"obj":"2A2","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes an insider threat actor?","options":["An external attacker with no prior relationship to the organization","A natural disaster affecting the organization's facilities","An individual with legitimate access who intentionally or negligently causes harm to the organization","A regulatory body auditing the organization's controls"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>An individual with legitimate access who intentionally or negligently causes harm to the organization</strong> — insiders already hold legitimate access, which is what makes them capable of bypassing perimeter controls, whether their harm is intentional or the result of negligence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>An external attacker with no prior relationship to the organization</b>: this describes an external threat actor, not an insider.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A natural disaster affecting the organization's facilities</b>: this is an environmental threat source, unrelated to insider access.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A regulatory body auditing the organization's controls</b>: a regulator performing oversight is not a threat actor at all.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-092","domain":2,"obj":"2A3","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the BEST reason to include process walkthroughs alongside technical vulnerability scanning in a vulnerability management program?","options":["Process walkthroughs are faster and cheaper than any technical scan","Technical scanning has been fully replaced by process walkthroughs in modern practice","Process walkthroughs surface weaknesses in workflows and controls that automated technical scans cannot detect","Process walkthroughs eliminate the need to track remediation of any findings"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Process walkthroughs surface weaknesses in workflows and controls that automated technical scans cannot detect</strong> — scanning tools find technical flaws, but only a walkthrough of an actual business process can reveal missing approvals, weak segregation of duties, or other procedural gaps.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Process walkthroughs are faster and cheaper than any technical scan</b>: relative speed or cost is not the reason walkthroughs are included; their value is in what they uniquely reveal.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Technical scanning has been fully replaced by process walkthroughs in modern practice</b>: both techniques remain necessary and complementary; neither has replaced the other.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Process walkthroughs eliminate the need to track remediation of any findings</b>: findings from any identification method still require tracking through to closure.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-093","domain":2,"obj":"2A4","diff":"easy","q":"A well-formed risk scenario should generally include which combination of elements?","options":["Only the name of the department responsible for the affected system","Only the date the scenario was written","A threat source, an exploitable condition, the affected asset, and the resulting business impact","Only a generic industry benchmark statistic"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A threat source, an exploitable condition, the affected asset, and the resulting business impact</strong> — combining these elements produces a scenario specific and complete enough to support meaningful likelihood and impact analysis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Only the name of the department responsible for the affected system</b>: a department name alone provides no analyzable risk content.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Only the date the scenario was written</b>: a creation date is an administrative detail, not scenario substance.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Only a generic industry benchmark statistic</b>: a generic statistic without organizational context cannot be evaluated as a specific scenario.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-094","domain":2,"obj":"2A5","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner combines asset-based identification, threat-based identification, and cross-functional scenario workshops for a major system migration project. What is the PRIMARY benefit of this combined approach over using only one technique?","options":["It guarantees the project will have zero residual risk after migration","It eliminates the need for the risk register to be updated afterward","It removes the requirement for business unit stakeholders to participate","It reduces blind spots by surfacing risks from multiple angles that a single technique would likely miss"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>It reduces blind spots by surfacing risks from multiple angles that a single technique would likely miss</strong> — combining techniques compensates for the blind spots inherent in any single method, producing a more comprehensive risk picture for a complex initiative like a system migration.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It guarantees the project will have zero residual risk after migration</b>: no combination of identification techniques can guarantee zero residual risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for the risk register to be updated afterward</b>: identified risks still must be logged and the register kept current regardless of technique.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It removes the requirement for business unit stakeholders to participate</b>: stakeholder participation remains valuable and is not eliminated by combining techniques.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-095","domain":2,"obj":"2B1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following would be the BEST key risk indicator (KRI) for monitoring rising exposure to unpatched critical vulnerabilities?","options":["The total number of employees in the IT department","The number of laptops issued to new hires last quarter","The average length of employee tenure in the security team","The percentage of critical vulnerabilities remaining open beyond the defined SLA window"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The percentage of critical vulnerabilities remaining open beyond the defined SLA window</strong> — this metric directly and quantifiably signals rising exposure to exploitation as overdue critical vulnerabilities accumulate, making it a strong leading indicator.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The total number of employees in the IT department</b>: staffing headcount does not measure vulnerability exposure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The number of laptops issued to new hires last quarter</b>: equipment issuance volume is unrelated to vulnerability risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The average length of employee tenure in the security team</b>: tenure is an HR metric with no direct link to vulnerability exposure.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-096","domain":2,"obj":"2B2","diff":"med","q":"A BIA ranks the order-management system as the organization's most critical process, with the shortest MTD of any system reviewed. What is the MOST appropriate use of this finding?","options":["Reduce monitoring of this system since it is already well understood","Assign the lowest budget priority since it was already reviewed first","Remove the system from future BIA cycles since its ranking is now established","Prioritize this system for the strongest resilience investment, fastest recovery capability, and closest ongoing risk monitoring"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Prioritize this system for the strongest resilience investment, fastest recovery capability, and closest ongoing risk monitoring</strong> — a system ranked most critical with the shortest tolerance for downtime should receive the greatest investment in resilience and the closest attention in ongoing risk monitoring.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduce monitoring of this system since it is already well understood</b>: understanding a system's criticality is a reason to monitor it more closely, not less.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Assign the lowest budget priority since it was already reviewed first</b>: order of review has no bearing on budget priority, which should follow criticality.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Remove the system from future BIA cycles since its ranking is now established</b>: BIAs must be repeated periodically since criticality and recovery needs can change over time.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-097","domain":2,"obj":"2B3","diff":"hard","q":"A risk register entry shows a treatment plan marked \"in progress\" for over two years with no milestone updates, while the assigned risk owner insists the risk is well managed informally. What is the MOST appropriate action for the risk practitioner?","options":["Accept the owner's informal assurance and close the entry","Reassign the risk to a different owner without discussion","Remove the treatment plan field from the register template entirely","Require the risk owner to formally document current status, remaining actions, and a realistic completion date, or escalate for a formal risk-acceptance decision"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Require the risk owner to formally document current status, remaining actions, and a realistic completion date, or escalate for a formal risk-acceptance decision</strong> — informal assurances are not a substitute for documented, verifiable status; the practitioner must ensure the register reflects reality or that the risk is formally escalated for a decision.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Accept the owner's informal assurance and close the entry</b>: closing based on an undocumented assurance risks masking an unresolved and possibly unmanaged risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reassign the risk to a different owner without discussion</b>: reassigning without engaging the current owner does not address the underlying documentation and accountability gap.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Remove the treatment plan field from the register template entirely</b>: removing the field would eliminate visibility into treatment status for all risks, not just this one.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-098","domain":2,"obj":"2B4","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST illustrates the use of the Delphi technique in risk analysis?","options":["Running a single Monte Carlo simulation to produce a probability distribution","Calculating ALE directly from verified historical loss data","Reviewing a vendor's SOC 2 report to assess a third party's controls","Independently collecting and iteratively refining anonymous expert judgments until a consensus risk rating emerges"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Independently collecting and iteratively refining anonymous expert judgments until a consensus risk rating emerges</strong> — the Delphi technique gathers anonymous expert input in rounds, refining estimates iteratively until convergence, which can support either qualitative or quantitative risk rating.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Running a single Monte Carlo simulation to produce a probability distribution</b>: this is a distinct statistical modeling technique, not the expert-consensus process the Delphi technique describes.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Calculating ALE directly from verified historical loss data</b>: this is a direct quantitative calculation, not an iterative expert-consensus method.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reviewing a vendor's SOC 2 report to assess a third party's controls</b>: this is a third-party assurance review activity, unrelated to the Delphi consensus technique.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-099","domain":2,"obj":"2B6","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner notes that residual risk for a legacy application dropped sharply after network segmentation was implemented, even though the application itself remains unpatched. What does this BEST illustrate?","options":["The inherent risk of the application must have decreased as well","The vulnerability no longer needs to be tracked in any capacity","Segmentation eliminates the need to ever patch the application","A compensating control can materially reduce residual risk even when the underlying vulnerability is not directly remediated"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A compensating control can materially reduce residual risk even when the underlying vulnerability is not directly remediated</strong> — segmentation reduces the exploitability and reach of the existing vulnerability, lowering residual risk, even though the vulnerability itself has not been fixed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The inherent risk of the application must have decreased as well</b>: inherent risk, by definition, is assessed before controls and does not change based on new compensating controls.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The vulnerability no longer needs to be tracked in any capacity</b>: the vulnerability still exists and should remain tracked and monitored in case segmentation is later removed or bypassed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Segmentation eliminates the need to ever patch the application</b>: a compensating control reduces risk but does not permanently remove the need to remediate the underlying vulnerability.</span>"},
{"id":"D2-100","domain":2,"obj":"2B7","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner is asked to justify why one \"medium-high\" risk on the heat map is being treated before several \"high\" risks. Which justification is MOST defensible?","options":["The practitioner personally prefers to address that risk first","The risk owner for the medium-high risk is a close colleague of the practitioner","The medium-high risk was the first one entered into the register chronologically","The medium-high risk has a significantly faster velocity of onset and lower treatment cost, making it more urgent and efficient to address first despite a marginally lower heat-map score"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The medium-high risk has a significantly faster velocity of onset and lower treatment cost, making it more urgent and efficient to address first despite a marginally lower heat-map score</strong> — a heat-map score is only one input; factors like speed of onset and feasibility/cost of treatment can legitimately justify reordering priority within a defensible, risk-based rationale.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The practitioner personally prefers to address that risk first</b>: personal preference is not a legitimate, defensible basis for prioritization.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The risk owner for the medium-high risk is a close colleague of the practitioner</b>: personal relationships must never influence objective risk prioritization.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The medium-high risk was the first one entered into the register chronologically</b>: entry order has no bearing on actual risk-based prioritization.</span>"},
]);

